BNP Paribas, Daimler, Rolls-Royce, ThyssenKrupp: European Equity Preview

-- B y   W h i t n e y   K i s l i n g
-- 
2011-05-12T04:00:04Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-05-12/bnp-paribas-daimler-thyssenkrupp-european-equity-preview.html
The following companies’ shares may
have unusual moves in European trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses.  The Stoxx  Europe  600 Index rose 0.3 percent to 283.73. The
Stoxx 50 Index advanced 0.2 percent to 2,653.45. The Euro Stoxx
50 Index, a benchmark for nations using the euro, climbed 0.1
percent to 2,942.43.  BNP Paribas (BNP)  SA:  France ’s largest bank isn’t
seeking major acquisitions in 2011 and will be “disciplined”
if opportunities arise for medium-sized purchases, Chief
Executive Officer Baudouin Prot said. The shares advanced 0.9
percent to 54.62 euros.  Daimler AG (DAI)  : The German carmaker and  Rolls-Royce
Group Plc (RR/)   may raise their Tognum AG bid by about 8
percent, valuing the engine maker at 3.42 billion euros ($4.86
billion), a person with direct knowledge of the matter said.
Daimler shares fell 0.5 percent to 50.80 euros.  Rolls-Royce rose 0.2 percent to 644.5 pence.  Dexia SA (DEXB)  : The bank, barred from paying cash
dividends to investors after receiving government rescue funds,
will distribute almost 102.6 million bonus shares to
shareholders, boosting its outsanding share count by 5.56
percent. Existing investors are entitled to one new share for
every 18 held. The shares rose 3.2 percent to 2.66 euros.  Electricite de France SA (EDF FP): Europe’s biggest
electricity producer’s EPR nuclear reactor under construction at
Flamanville in northern France is still scheduled to come on
line in 2014,  Agence France-Presse  reported, citing the site
manager. The shares gained 0.8 percent to 28.62 euros.  International Consolidated Airlines Group SA (IAG LN): The
company’s British Airways unit may be close to resolving the
dispute with some of its cabin crew that has triggered 22 days
of strikes over the past two years, the  BBC  reported, without
attribution. The stock retreated 0.8 percent to 246.4 pence.  Thales SA (HO)  : Europe’s largest defense-electronics
producer said it had first-quarter revenue of 2.52 billion
euros, compared with 2.48 billion euros a year earlier. The
shares rose 0.6 percent to 30.22 euros.  ThyssenKrupp AG (TKA)  :  Germany ’s largest steelmaker’s
employees have approved a company reorganization after job cuts
because of redundancies were eliminated from the agreement
Deutsche Presse Agentur reported, citing comments from the head
of the workers’ council Thomas Schlenz today. Shares fell 0.4
percent to 33.09 euros.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Whitney Kisling in New York at 
 wkisling@bloomberg.net   To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Nick Baker at   nbaker7@bloomberg.net  